I"<p>Yixin Zou (she/her) is an incoming tenure-track faculty member at the Max Planck Institute for Security and Privacy. Her research interests span human-computer interaction, privacy, and security, with an emphasis on improving consumersâ€™ adoption of protective behaviors and supporting the digital safety of at-risk populations. Her research has been recognized with a Best Paper Award at the Symposium on Usable Privacy and Security (SOUPS), two Honorable Mentions at the ACM Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems (CHI), and the 2022 John Karat Usable Privacy and Security Student Research Award. She has given multiple invited talks at the US Federal Trade Commission, and she co-led the research effort that produced the opt-out icon in the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA). She has also collaborated with industry partners at NortonLifeLock, Meta, and Mozilla. She holds a PhD in Information from the University of Michigan and a BSc in Advertising from the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.</p>
